        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>Friday.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p><anchor xml:id="ann.a1" type="annotationStart"/>The shells which needed describing, are now described.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Shall I send you the MS?</p>
<p>The Conception <hi rend="underline">Nautilus</hi> I cannot satisfactorily identify with any other. I propose to call it <hi rend="underline">N. D’Orbignyanus</hi> if you have no objection. It comes very near some lower &amp; middle cretaceous species.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I send the M<hi rend="superscript">ss</hi>. wanted.</p>
<p>I leave the Fuego Ancyloceras unnamed. Give D’Orbigny’s supposed identif<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. of it. It is however not in a state sufficiently secure for my conscience to hang upon its horn.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>The Terra del fuego fragments impress me with the notion that they indicate cretaceous epoch—probably the early part.<anchor xml:id="ann.a2" type="annotationEnd"/></p>
<p>Such also is the impression I take up (&amp; more firmly) from those of Corderilla of Central Chili.<ref target="#foot.f5"/> I send that M<hi rend="superscript">ss</hi>. with the other. I am now ready to see Sowerby.<ref target="#foot.f6"/> <anchor xml:id="ann.a3" type="annotationStart"/>If he is not coming tomorrow, I will be in my office all Monday.</p>
<p>Our survey reports are now out. I wish I could send you a copy of my paper<ref target="#foot.f7"/> but as yet have not been able to lay hands on one for myself<anchor xml:id="ann.a4" type="annotationEnd"/></p>
<p>Ever, most sincerely | Edward Forbes</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="annotations">
                <note target="#ann.a1" targetEnd="#ann.a2"><hi rend="italic">crossed pencil</hi></note>
                <note> 2.3 lower &amp; middle cretaceous] <hi rend="italic">underl pencil</hi> </note>
                <note target="#ann.a3" targetEnd="#ann.a4"><hi rend="italic">crossed pencil</hi></note>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The conjectured date is the first Friday after the announcement of the publication of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2580.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">E. Forbes 1846</ref> in <hi rend="italic">Memoirs of the Geological Survey</hi> (<hi rend="italic">The Publishers’ Circular</hi>, 1 August 1846, listing the volume as ‘just published’ in the period 13–29 July).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Forbes described CD’s Secondary fossil shells in the appendix of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Forbes eventually decided it resembled two species from the Upper Greensand (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref>, pp. 127, 265).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">According to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref>, p. 152, Forbes agreed with Orbigny that the fossil was early Cretaceous.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Noted by CD in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref>, p. 193.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4479.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Brettingham Sowerby Jr</ref>, who illustrated the fossil shells for the plates in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7343.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">South America</hi></ref>. Forbes and George Brettingham Sowerby prepared descriptions for the appendix.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2580.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">E. Forbes 1846</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
